State MSM Profile: Connecticut

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Connecticut

An estimated 43,312 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Connecticut in 2013, representing 1.0% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 1,334,105 adult men of Connecticut, 3.2% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Connecticut resided in counties within medium or small metropolitan areas (44.6%). Including both central and fringe counties, 51.1% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Connecticut, 2013

MSM in Connecticut Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Connecticut, Hartford County had the largest population of MSM at 16,767, representing 38.7% of all MSM in the state. Hartford County also had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Connecticut at 5.1%. This was greater than the percentage for Connecticut as a whole, which was 3.2% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Connecticut Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Hartford-West Hartford-East Hartford Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Hartford-West Hartford-East Hartford MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Connecticut at 22,133, or 51.1% of all MSM in the state. Of the 455,231 adult men in Hartford-West Hartford-East Hartford, an estimated 4.9% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk MSA had a population of 8,245 MSM, or 19.0% of all MSM in Connecticut. Of the 335,063 adult men in Bridgeport-Stamford-Norwalk, an estimated 2.5% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




New Haven-Milford Metropolitan Statistical Area

The New Haven-Milford MSA had a population of 7,643 MSM, or 17.6% of all MSM in Connecticut. Of the 319,114 adult men in New Haven-Milford, an estimated 2.4% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Norwich-New London Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Norwich-New London MSA had a population of 2,450 MSM, or 5.7% of all MSM in Connecticut. Of the 107,291 adult men in Norwich-New London, an estimated 2.3% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Worcester Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Worcester MSA overlaps two states: Connecticut and Massachusetts. The Connecticut portion of the MSA had 992 MSM, or 2.3% of all MSM in the state and 11.0% of the 9,037 MSM in the MSA. Of 45,117 adult men in the Connecticut part of Worcester, 2.2% were MSM. This was less than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 2.6% of adult men (9,037 out of 346,199).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
